Powerlifting Analysis on IPF Tournaments¶

Powerlifting is a strength-based sport where athletes compete by performing three compound movements: squat, bench press, and deadlift. Each of these lifts can be loaded incredibly heavy and each challenge different muscle groups. Athletes train to lift the heaviest weight possible in all three events in a single day in order to achieve the high possible total. Powerlifting tournaments are hosted at different levels (locally, state, regionally, nationally, and internationally) and split into different divisions based on the athletes age, sex, and weight to ensure a balanced competition. These competitions attract athletes from all ranges of age groups with different amounts of experience.

In this project we look at data for powerlifting tournaments. We will look specifically at tournaments hosted by the International Powerlifting Federation (IPF) as they are one of the largest organizations resposible for hosting quality, high-standard competitions internationally. They do this by following a technical rulebook which is enforced by all of their affiliate organizers (technical rulebook).

The dataset we will be using comes from the Openpowerlifting Data Service. They are a community of powerlifters who scrape the internet for tournament information and append it to their database. They provide a great service to the powerlifting community by creating a permanent archive of the world's powerlifting data and providing it in convenient formats. In addition to the datasets, they have clear documentation on their table, columns, and values which makes it a perfect dataset for analysis.

On the Openpowerlifting site, we obtain the data for powerlifting tournaments by the IPF and affiliates only. This is to ensure data integrity and accuracy of our dataset and thus our analysis. The main purpose of these tournaments is to determine who the strongest athlete is. We will explore the data to determine what factors contribute to determining an athlete's strength and what is required of an athlete in order to win a tournament. Some examples of athlete attributes which play a major role are their age, sex, and weight. We will explore how much each of the athlete's events (squat, deadlift, and bench press) contribute towards their total strength. Next, we will explore the probability or requirements for an athlete to potentially win a tournament. Finally, we will use regression algorithms to predict the strength levels of athletes.

Data Collection¶

We use Python3 and libraries such as pandas, matplotlib and scikit-learn to perform our analysis and create our models.

  • Pandas is useful to store datasets, filtering data, and performing search queries.
  • Matplotlib is our main tool to create visualizations in Python
  • Scikit-Learn contains models for regression models we want to implement and error metrics to measure accuracy

Acquiring the Data¶

The data can be downloaded from the OpenPowerlifting site here. On the site, we can follow the sidebar to "Bulk CSV Downloads" and select which dataset we want to use. There is a complete dataset containing information from all tournaments and another which only contains information about tournaments hosted by the IPF or its affiliates. Additionally, there is documentation for the columns of the dataset if more information is desired. For our analysis, we will use the dataset with only IPF and affiliate information to avoid unnecessary work

In [82]:
data = pd.read_csv('openipf.csv', low_memory = False)

In this dataset, we will focus primarily on these columns:

  • Sex - Sex category athlete competed in
  • Event - Tells us which lifts the athlete competed in [S] - Squat, [B] - Bench, [D] - Deadlift (or some permutation of the three)
  • Age - Athlete's age in Kg
  • AgeClass - What age range they are categorized as under IPF rules
  • Division - Name of their division (based on age and body weight)
  • BodyweightKg - Athlete's weight in Kg
  • WeightClassKg - Athlete's weight class in Kg
  • Best3SquatKg, Best3BenchKg, Best3DeadliftKg - Their heaviest successful lift out of three attempts
  • TotalKg - The total of their heaviest three successful lifts (empty if one of three lifts failed). This will also be our main indicator of an athlete's strength.
  • Date

Data Cleansing¶

Now that we have our data, let's begin cleaning. Since we know our data is merged from different IPF affiliates, there will be some inconsistencies as different affiliates can split divisions by different age or weight ranges. As per the IPF technical rule book, athletes are first divided by sex, then age group, and finally weight. These columns are all important for identifying relationships and trends between athletes, we will remove any data that has null values for columns:

  • Age
  • Sex
  • BodyWeightKg
  • TotalKg
In [84]:
data = data.dropna(subset = ['Age', 'Sex', 'BodyweightKg', 'TotalKg'])

We will also remove any rows where the athlete's age is not recorded (as 0), recorded correctly, or athlete's who didn't qualify to compete. IPF tournaments begin at age 14 so we will filter anything beneath that.

In [85]:
data = data[data['Age'] >= 14]

data = data.drop('WeightClassKg', axis = 'columns')
data = data.drop('AgeClass', axis = 'columns')

We now recreate these same classes using IPF standards. For males, their age class is split from

  • Open, All age groups 14 and above
  • Sub-Junior, day he reaches 14 to 18
  • Junior, day he reaches 19 to 23
  • Master I, day he reaches 40 to 49
  • Master II, day he reaches 50 to 59
  • Master III, day he reaches 60 to 69
  • Master IV, 70 and upwards

For females, similar divisions

  • Open, All age groups 14 and above
  • Sub-Junior, day he reaches 14 to 18
  • Junior, day he reaches 19 to 23
  • Master I, day he reaches 40 to 49
  • Master II, day he reaches 50 to 59
  • Master III, day he reaches 60 to 69
  • Master IV, 70 and upwards

And for Mx, we will assume the same ranges.

  • Open, All age groups 14 and above
  • Sub-Junior, day he reaches 14 to 18
  • Junior, day he reaches 19 to 23
  • Master I, day he reaches 40 to 49
  • Master II, day he reaches 50 to 59
  • Master III, day he reaches 60 to 69
  • Master IV, 70 and upwards
In [89]:
AgeClass = []
Division = []
for index, row in data.iterrows():
    if row['Age'] >= 14 and row['Age'] <= 18:
        AgeClass.append('14-18')
        Division.append('Sub-Junior')
    elif row['Age'] >= 19 and row['Age'] <= 23:
        AgeClass.append('19-23')
        Division.append('Junior')
    elif row['Age'] >= 40 and row['Age'] <= 49:
        AgeClass.append('40-49')
        Division.append('Master I')
    elif row['Age'] >= 50 and row['Age'] <= 59:
        AgeClass.append('50-59')
        Division.append('Master II')
    elif row['Age'] >= 60 and row['Age'] <= 69:
        AgeClass.append('60-69')
        Division.append('Master III')
    elif row['Age'] >= 70 and row['Age'] <= 79:
        AgeClass.append('70-79')
        Division.append('Master IV')
    else:
        AgeClass.append('Any')
        Division.append('Open')
data['AgeClass'] = AgeClass
data['Division'] = Division

Now we follow a similar procedure for creating the WeightClassKg column except now there exists differences in the weight range between male and female athletes. As there is only 6 athletes under the Mx category, we will just categorize them in similar ranges as the male athletes. The value in the new WeightClassKg column will be the upper limit of the weight class. For the final class, the no upper bound class will be denoted as 1000.

Exploratory Analysis¶

Now that we've categorized the athlete's division by IPF standards, we can begin exploring the data. As we've seen, the IPF goes to great lengths to create balanced divisions in order for athlete's to have a fair competition. This is done by accounting for the athlete's age, weight, and sex. We are curious as to how strong the relationship between these factors have on an athlete's strength individually or in some combination.

Graphing Strength vs. Body Weight¶

Let's look at the relationship between an athlete's body weight and strength. Strength will be measured through the TotalKG columns for each athlete. This is the total amount of weight an athlete moved in all three events combined. We will only look at athletes who lifted in all three events. We know an athlete performs all three events if the value in 'Event' is equal to 'SBD'.

In [91]:
tempSBD = data[data['Event'] == 'SBD']

plt.xticks(fontsize = 12)
plt.yticks(fontsize = 12)

There is large variability between an athlete's strength and body weight. The two variables do seem to share a positive linear relationship where as the body weight of the athlete increases, so does their total strength. However, there are some visible outliers where athlete's at a higher body weight (~200 Kg) don't entirely perform better than those at a lower body weight. It makes sense that the IPF would want to break athlete's into separate weight categories as there is a clear advantage for heavier athletes. We have a lot of data so let's split the athlete's by sex (where Mx athlete's will be combined with the male athlete's data) to see if the same trend is true across both groups.

Comparing Event's Contribution to Total Lift Based on Athlete's Age and Weight Category¶

Now we want to look at how much each event (Squat, Bench, and Deadlift) contributes towards the total lifting weight. We want to see which lifts are an athlete's strongest and possibly what athletes should focus on to maximize their total lift potential. We will look at the average strength between each age and weight group.

To perform our analysis, we must split the athlete data by their sex, age, and weight. We will use the same temp_F and temp_M data as earlier to only look at athlete's who participated in all three events (since temp_F and temp_M both only contain athlete information who participated in all three events). Then, we will sort the datasets by age class then weight class (to make our presentation nicer). Finally, we will group the data by all possible age and weight classes to acquire mean values for the best of each three events and their total strength.

In [102]:
temp_F = temp_F.sort_values(by = ['AgeClass', 'WeightClassKg'])
In [103]:
temp_M = temp_M.sort_values(by = ['AgeClass', 'WeightClassKg'])
In [104]:
categories_F = temp_F.groupby(by = ['AgeClass', 'WeightClassKg']).mean()
In [105]:
categories_M = temp_M.groupby(by = ['AgeClass', 'WeightClassKg']).mean()

Now we create our categories for each combination of age and weight class. These will be useful for identifying our bar in the chart.

For female athletes, it seems that across all age groups there is a linear increase in strength as their body weight increases. Finally, the squat comes at second accounting almost as much the deadlift (around some age groups) at about 31 to 39 percent.

How strong is a winner?¶

Now that we've looked at the relationships between strength based on age, sex, and events, let's attempt to identify how strong an athlete must be to win a tournmanet. How much stronger an athlete has to be can be defined by comparing them to the average results of athlete's in their same age and weight group.

We must first identify the winners in our database. According to the documentation, column 'Place' records the place of the lifter in the given division at the end of the meet. We care solely about individuals who took first place so we will filter for that. We will the find the averages strength for the winners amongst their respective age and weight categories.

Let's filter for solely first place winners.

In [118]:
winners = tempSBD[tempSBD['Place'] == '1']

Now we average all winners amongst themselves.

In [60]:
grouped_winners = winners.groupby(by = ['Sex', 'AgeClass', 'WeightClassKg']).mean()

Now we look at the total average amongst the total population.

In [119]:
grouped_total = tempSBD.groupby(by = ['Sex', 'AgeClass', 'WeightClassKg']).mean()

Finally, we calculate the difference between the two groups. Say we only care about age, body weight, best lift for each event, and the total.

In [120]:
grouped_total = grouped_total[['Age', 'BodyweightKg', 'Best3SquatKg', 'Best3BenchKg', 'Best3DeadliftKg', 'TotalKg']]
grouped_winners = grouped_winners[['Age', 'BodyweightKg', 'Best3SquatKg', 'Best3BenchKg', 'Best3DeadliftKg', 'TotalKg']]
In [121]:
diff = grouped_total.compare(grouped_winners)

Now that we have the two groups, we first look at the male athletes.

In this figure we plot the average strength of all male powerlifters respective to their age and weight group. Then we plot their average alongside powerlifters who won at their tournament and comparing their strength levels. Through this figure we see that athletes are not astronomically stronger than the majority of powerlifters at these tournaments. However, the difference is still significant. We see the biggest difference in strength averages in our 'Any' age group which makes sense since that group has the largest variance between athlete's.

There are some strange occurences in the previous plot where the 70-79 age group has two weight classes, the 120 and the 1000 (no limit) have population averages greater than the winners average. It's possible that athlete's were disqualified for some reason and their lift wasn't elgible to win. It would have to be a lot of athletes however to affect the average that drastically.

Unlike the male athletes, the female athletes appear to have a larger discrepancy in strength between the average population and winners. This difference is much more significant and can be seen in earlier age groups. There are still some flukes around the 70-79 age group where winners average strength is somehow lower than that of the general population.

Predicting Strength in Athlete's¶

Linear Regression for Athlete's¶

We have seen now that through different combinations of categories, there is a significant relationship between an athletes body weight and the total amount of weight they can lift. Now, we will attempt to create a regression model which attempts to predict the amount of weight an athlete can lift based on their sex, age, and body weight. This model will calculate the expected total weight.

We will filter our data to contain only the columns we care about.

In [124]:
lift_data = tempSBD[['Sex', 'Age', 'BodyweightKg', 'Best3SquatKg', 'Best3BenchKg', 'Best3DeadliftKg', 'TotalKg']]

Now that we have our lift data, we check to see if we have any categorical variables that require attention. Which there is, for column 'Sex' we have string variables 'M', 'F', and 'Mx'. This means we must one-hot encode the values in this column. One-hot encoding is a process which turns categorical variables into individual columns for each unique value using 1's and 0's to indicate their value. This allows our regression model to read and use the data.

In [125]:
temp_onehot = pd.get_dummies(lift_data['Sex'])
In [126]:
lift_data = lift_data.drop('Sex', axis = 1)
In [127]:
lift_data = lift_data.join(temp_onehot)

We will create athlete_data with just the athlete's sex, age, and bodyweight. The we will use the TotalKg column as our target for prediction.

In [128]:
athlete_data = lift_data[['M', 'F', 'Mx', 'Age', 'BodyweightKg']]
strength_data = lift_data[['TotalKg']]

Next, we will initialize our regression models. We will use two different models available on scikit, the k nearest neighbor model and a decision tree model. This is in order to compare the accuracy of models and make sure we are getting accurate results.

In [129]:
neigh = KNeighborsRegressor(algorithm = 'kd_tree', n_neighbors = 5)
In [130]:
dectree = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state = 22)

In order to fit a model, we must split the data into training and test sets. This is done in order to teach the model what our expected result should look like and then validate those results with values whose results we already know, but that the model does not know.

In [132]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(athlete_data, strength_data, test_size = 0.25, random_state = 22)

Now that we have our training data, we fit both models with it.

In [133]:
neigh.fit(X_train, y_train)
dectree.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[133]:
DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=22)

Now with both models trained, we can test it using our testing data.

In [134]:
y_bykNN = neigh.predict(X_test)
y_bydectree = dectree.predict(X_test)

Our model has predicted the expected strength for these athletes, now what? In order to determine if our model is effective or not, we must compare it to our actual data. We use three major measurements to test for error and which ultimately tells us the effectiveness of our models. There are mean squared error (MSE), root mean squared error (RMSE), and mean absolute error (MAE).

Starting with MSE:

In [135]:
kNN_MSE = mean_squared_error(y_bykNN, y_test)
tree_MSE = mean_squared_error(y_bydectree, y_test)
if abs(kNN_MSE) < abs(tree_MSE):
    print('kNN')
    print (kNN_MSE)
else:
    print('dectree')
    print(tree_MSE)

kNN
10448.633199618404

We see that our mean squared error is rather large. This is because MSE tends to amplify errors that are greatly off versus errors that are smaller. We can get a different interpretation from our other metrics

In [136]:
kNN_RMSE = mean_squared_error(y_bykNN, y_test, squared = False)
tree_RMSE = mean_squared_error(y_bydectree, y_test, squared = False)
if abs(kNN_RMSE) < abs(tree_RMSE):
    print('kNN')
    print (kNN_RMSE)
else:
    print('dectree')
    print(tree_RMSE)

kNN
102.21855604350124

The root mean squared error does a similar calculation as the MSE except it provides it to us in a more readable form.

In [137]:
kNN_MAE = mean_absolute_error(y_bykNN, y_test)
tree_MAE = mean_absolute_error(y_bydectree, y_test)
if abs(kNN_MAE) < abs(tree_MAE):
    print('kNN')
    print (kNN_MAE)
else:
    print('dectree')
    print(tree_MAE)

kNN
79.02081041951077

The mean absolute error gives us the actual different between the prediced and actual value. This mean that on average, our prediction is about 79 kg off. This is a big difference since that is equivalent to about ~ 175 lbs. This sort of error comes from outliers in our data from athletes who are far above the population.

We see that the error for our k nearest neighbor model has a lower error value across all our metrics. We will attempt to plot our results for the regression model.

In [138]:
figure11, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (35, 15))
ax = plt.axes(projection = '3d')
ax.scatter3D(X_test['Age'].head(30), X_test['BodyweightKg'].head(30), y_test[0:30], s = 40, c = 'g')
ax.scatter3D(X_test['Age'].head(30), X_test['BodyweightKg'].head(30), y_bykNN[0:30], s = 40, c = 'r')

This 3d plot shows the estimated level of strength for an athlete from our k nearest neighbor model compared to the actual strength of the athlete. We are able to see along which axis the model is most off by. We see that the model tends to underestimate the strength of the athlete's in our training data.

Conclusion¶

Powerlifting is an amazing sport which pushes our bodies to grow and adapt. Thanks to the services of the OpenPowerlifting group, we were able to navigate the data science pipeline in order to receive insight on this sport. Through this analysis, we explored relationships between strength and an athletes age, sex, and weight. All of which can effect the total amount of weight an individual can move. We also see which events are best to load heavy and contribute most to an individuals total strength. We also identifed what is required of athletes to win events based on their age and weight class. Athletes and coaches can use this data to their advantage in order to become stronger and even win tournaments.

This tutorial also demonstrated how to create a regression model in order to predict strength levels of athletes based on their sex, weight, and age. This tool can be generalized to different datasets in order to predict a target variable based on some list of attributes. We also determined the magnitude of error with these models using metrics like mean squared error, root mean squared error, and mean absolute error.
